text: that‚Äôs me, sitting on the right. i was granted early selection / scholarship entry to the australian defence force academy in the 90‚Äôs to undertake army officer training. we heard early on, about the guy that hung himself in his closet, then the next year a girl died after falling from her room in the lines, then one of my friends jumped off a building in canberra. i had my own struggles with the abuse and harassment that went on and later developed anxiety and depression, not from deployment, but from the experiences i had whilst training and working with the army. things that should never have happed, that‚Äôs where i lived and worked. i should have felt safe and supported, but i often didn‚Äôt. i was reading about how #hrhprincewilliamofwales struggled to get anyone to support heads together, his mental health charity because people still fear the stigma. i am always going to be vocal about my experiences of trauma; from my childhood, from the military, from the scenes of carnage, violence and deaths witnessed as a police officer. i know that for me, talking about that helps so much. the more we talk, the more we share, helps others to realise how important mental health is, and, helps those struggling through to know they‚Äôre not alone üíõ take care of each other out there üí´ #icare #mentalhealthawareness #headstogether #youthmentalhealth #ruok #1in4 #metoo #anxietysucks #itsoktonotbeok #reachout #askthequestion #areyouok

more on chloe:
chloe melas is an entertainment reporter for cnn, covering all things entertainment and hollywood for the network across platforms. melas is based out of cnn's new york bureau.
in addition to her breaking news coverage of the entertainment industry, melas has done extensive reporting in the #metoo era, reporting exclusively on sexual harassment and misconduct allegations on high profile figures, including kevin spacey, harvey weinstein, and morgan freeman.
before joining cnn, melas spent nearly seven years at hollywoodlife where she was a senior entertainment reporter. in 2013, chloe became one of the co-hosts of vh1's hit morning show, the gossip table. and prior to hollywoodlife, she was a news assistant for cnn.
melas is a graduate of auburn university where she majored in radio, tv & film. she grew up in both dallas, tx, and atlanta, ga and currently resides in manhattan with her husband and son.

text:
thursday throwback ~ this is the only photo i have of me as a child.
i have absolutely no other piece of evidence that i existed tbh! 
it‚Äôs a strange feeling. it makes me sad initially. sad that i can‚Äôt show my children pictures of me, sad that i don‚Äôt have the silly photos to show friends or partners so that we can laugh at them...
but then i think, well i was a skinny, goofy, knobbly kneed kid anyway so meh!! i have the memories in my mind of my childhood and i‚Äôve learned to filter through only the good & i have a voice that i can use to tell people the parts of my childhood that i want too.
i wish i could tell that 7year old blonde girl, that one day she is going to be a confident, happy, loved woman & that everything she was going through, would shape her into a strong mother with an unstoppable voice. 
a picture tells a completely different story to what is actually happening & i think that‚Äôs something we need to remember on this funny little app üñ§

text:
sure sis, looking good makes us feel good. but some things are more than skin deep. like our mental and emotional health. culture has taught us to prioritize our appearance, our image, our beauty. we spend obscene amounts of time and $$ (up to $225k over our lifetime to be exact) on clothes, makeup, gym memberships, tanning salons, hairdressers, nails, cosmetic procedures, etc...but how much do we spend on our mental health?
.
yes these outward factors contribute to the betterment of our inner mental health, but is our intention in spending money on these things to feel good or look good? i can spend all the money on making the outside look good, but if the inside isn‚Äôt operating at its best...then it‚Äôs just a shell, a mask, a facade. what happens when we remove our masks, what are we left with? something we‚Äôre happy with, something we‚Äôre proud of?
.
i say screw popular opinion, screw the stigmas and judgements surrounding mental health. my belief? it‚Äôs prioritizing from the inside then out. besides, the better you feel...the better you look anyways.

text:
#guidemyrelationships: 
the topic of sexual abuse in teen girls is an issue that is often swept under the rug. but with the recent #metoo movement and #survivingrkelly #docuseries has opened up the conversation for many. with these statistics, we can no longer ignore. 
one in 9 girls under the age of 18 experience sexual abuse or assault at the hands of an adult.

82% of all victims under 18 are female.

females ages 16-19 are 4 times more likely than the general population to be victims of rape, attempted rape, or sexual assault. 
the effects of child sexual abuse can be long-lasting and affect the victim's mental health. victims are more likely than non-victims to experience the following mental health challenges:

about 4 times more likely to develop symptoms of drug abuse
about 4 times more likely to experience ptsd as adults
about 3 times more likely to experience a major depressive episode as adults.
#sexualabuse #teengirls #guidemyheart #jadapinkettsmith #redtabletalk #jada #willowsmith

text: last one year has been soo crazy that i don't have words to express! i have gone through soo many phases from being a victim of sexual harassment, bullying to having the courage to fight back, not give up. i have had sleepless nights fighting the demons inside and out. there were days i wanted to not go through it anymore; i wanted the torture to end!!! i was depressed, signed up for therapy; i went without sleep for over two months and was a bag of nerves. and in the last one year, if i haven't returned your calls, it was because i was beyond broken. i used to fake the smile and to make things worse i didn't have too many people supporting me. guess in a battle between power and truth, power wins, but i knew that i had to survive and i did and how. what kept me going? hope. it's the most powerful thing in this world. i am still recovering and guess it's going to take time. now, i wake up every morning and thank god for giving me the courage to fight it all. always remember no matter how dark the darkness is, one must focus on seeing the light. someone will still be happier, prettier, more courageous but remember they will never be you! you're all that you have and make sure you don't give up and always believe that things will get better. #survivor #metoo #sexualharassment #mystory #eat #pray #love #believe #hope #depression #woundedsoldier #bangalore #diaryofaprettytraveller

text:
why is paddling so therapeutic? here are some ideas:
-
mindfulness:  when focused on ‚Äúnot falling‚Äù the mind can not focus on those old, intrusive thoughts.  it is a vessel to being in the moment, focused on the present, which is one of the four key areas of dialectical behavioral therapy, a powerful tool for processing powerful emotions.
-
distress tolerance: as a survivor of violence and the resulting anxiety/panic attacks, i know how useful it is to experience the body shaking while doing something that means the shaking is good! yes! the body shakes while gaining stability on the board, and it is an evolution of power.  this is another key area of dialectical behavioral therapy that naturally occurs with paddle boarding.
-
building social supports: how nice is it to bond with others over a fun activity, where no one has to talk?  paddlers can just laugh, enjoy, support one another and enjoy powerful moments together.
-
build upon success: eventually, we learn to move the board forward, make it go where we want, move to our knees and at times‚Ä¶stand!  for those whose lives have made them feel powerless and ineffective, this is big! it restores hope for the future to promote post traumatic growth
-
follow us! we‚Äôre fundraising for our therapist and the expansion of our paddle therapy program for survivors of violence! enjoy watching it all expand with us!! -

text:
‚Äúbut no one‚Äôs saying it‚Äôs not ok to be a man.‚Äù ok. well you‚Äôre not me. 
sometimes i feel like saying, ‚Äúgood thing i‚Äôm gay, or else i‚Äôd have to deal with being a white, straight man!‚Äù i have my minority status checked. 
but really, i‚Äôm one who has dealt with shame around being a man, we‚Äôll call it broken masculinity. in elementary school, junior high school and at church, i heard how some adults and girls would talk about guys. i unconsciously latched on to the negative things that were said about men and boys. women‚Äôs church meetings were usually about divine worth and men‚Äôs church meetings were usually about how we needed to respect women and stop watching porn. there‚Äôs a lot that fed into my shame around being a boy and a man. i often feel like the #metoo movement adds to that shame. either it‚Äôs my fault or i have to apologize for my whole gender. not that the metoo movement *is* about that, but that‚Äôs how it *felt.*
what‚Äôs important now is reclaiming what it means to be a man and perhaps even find some pride in it. who knows? maybe a ‚Äúplain old‚Äù straight white man has had a story like mine.

text:
unwanted sexual advances usually come from people you know or who you are in close association with. at the young age of 22 my boss began making gestures towards me, over complimenting my work, and calling me to his office to woo me. he implicated his intentions by trying to make me feel like i was special. he encouraged me to be loyal to him because it came with rewards.

i was young, inexperienced and plain didn't know what to do. i  tried to confide in a co-worker who didn't know how to advise me and in uncertain ways began making me feel as though i was in some way encouraging this man.

i was a young, single mother of two and i needed that job to help my sister pay the rent and care for my girls. it was the perfect job, not far from home and paid well. the potential for me to become entangled in this affair was prevalent but i didn't want to yield. 
when i could no longer tolerate this man's advances i quit my job never knowing that what he was doing was a crime or that i could have pressed charges. 
i left that job and never spoke about it again to anyone. i just moved on with my life. the me too movement is encouraging women to rise from the shadows and that's good, but i think men should rise out of the shadows too. #metoo #sexualharassment #tellsomeonewhoyoucantrust #knowthedifference #loveüíölove #misscurrycares
name: Miss Curry Cares

in physical intimacy, the ethos i learned while growing up was that the boy would try to get ‚Äúas far‚Äù with the girl as she would ‚Äúlet him‚Äù and if she said, no, he would pause for a moment and then try again. it was a level of offense and defense with women holding the role of a traffic cop on the actions in a makeout session. during this time, the word consent was not part of the world‚Äôs lexicon. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
today the popular phrase, "not saying 'no' doesn't mean 'yes,'" is making the "consent is sexy" campaign just that sexy. this violence prevention effort to make consent both popular and sexy has finally come to drive a long awaited discussion around the principle of respecting each person for their sense of pleasure and judgment. this movement is truly part of the larger gender equity discussion happening worldwide. consent is not only sexy it‚Äôs mandatory!

you‚Äôll see the strength and service in family, work, friends, your beloved and even men holding signs. üòä

when you heal, you‚Äôll heal women generations before, after and around you.  and the men around change.  cool shit, huh?

text:
thanks facebook for ads like these that  suggest a keyring will save us from being raped, ignoring that perpetrators are more often than not, known to the person than they are the stranger on the street, when we have our keys out between our fingers to protect ourselves...( another way victims are told to 'not become another statistic')
.
i don't have stats on how this item has been tested and i'm not disputing it's possible effectiveness but am pissed off at the marketing here which once again places the responsibility on victims and comes targeted to women at a time where a woman in australia was killed due to violence (though this is frequent enough now that it could be any week in australia)
.
i'm not saying we don't have to take precautions (i wish it was not the case) but i am saying that an insensitive ad about a rape protection device being sold with a bunch of emojis like it's just another gadget is really shitty marketing but thanks again media for letting women know that their rape could have been avoided if they, the victim had a keyring
.
.

.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
i‚Äôve been watching figure skating for 14 years now. every friend of mine knows how much i love this sport. i thought my love¬†for skating would last forever. but now, i feel really disappointed about the so called skating community. i used to believe in every beautiful narrative about this sport, naive as i was.

i‚Äôm so shocked when i heard about the death of john coughlin. i feel deeply sorry for his family and friends and i totally understand that people need time to mourn and to express their grief. what really concerns me is, however, that there are girls who said they have been sexually assaulted by john and have reported this situation to #safesport. i know we can‚Äôt say that john is guilty simply based on the accusation and the suspension he got later but the fact that there are alleged victims does make things different. i dare hope you skaters and coaches can delete some of your awful posts that might be seen by those alleged victims. or just simply acknowledge their existence. you may not have realized that they are suffering, too. your mourning in public and your praises for john being a good man would hurt them pretty bad. 
and what‚Äôs worse, i‚Äôve seen people from your community fucking around calling those girls liars and asking for their names, which is extremely horrible. oh yeah, the very few people who did research and covered this situation properly is now getting death threats.

after going through all these, i don‚Äôt really have faith in a safe environment for young kids who are learning and doing figure skating. they are so vulnerable being exposed to such a community and to such people who don‚Äôt think they deserve the truth. 
i understand that it would be hard for you people standing out and asking for a closure to those accusations. but i‚Äôm still waiting for someone to come forward and do something, at least press your association into further investigation. maybe i‚Äôm asking too much. am i?

text:
warning, this may upset you if you have a closed perspective or if you're a bikram advocate. ‚ú®
turning a blind eye eh? why is this happening in so many communities? ‚ú®
i was never an anusara yogi (i'm just not into dogmatic systems of yoga), but i studied the method for many years. in early 2011 @grahams made me this shirt when teachers (including 2 of mine) all over the globe left the anusara affiliation due to the man who was heading the show. it was my way of protesting without a lot of words.  it was amazing to see how many yogis i knew who were willing to abandon the name that brought them great success, taking a risk and maybe even losing their careers. it was heartbreaking to see and it was also beautiful to watch for that shit takes guts. ‚ú®
when the leader of a yogic system or community is obviously bi-passing ethical principles and creating harm, something needs to happen, right?
‚ú®
i've been in the works of writing about the insanity inside of yoga and so-called 'yoga communities' surrounding ethical issues that are extremely ignored. it is so easy to see how these cycles keep continuing and it makes me cringe that it is mainly woman turning the eye on this issue for this is who is mainly running the yoga industry!. fuck, i've been called names and gossiped about because i have fired teachers for sleeping and being sexual with students! i have and will kick students out for being inappropriate. what's even crazier is a male i kicked out for multiple accounts of sexual harassment is actually teaching yoga!!! harm and misconduct? in yoga? i see it all the time and it blows my fucking mind. ‚ú®
being a child of sexual abuse i cannot stand for this shit anymore and hear woman and men justify their actions of supporting criminals name because they weren't personally hurt or affected by this person. it's nutzo. being the leader of a community, it is time to actually speak and stand up. 
so what do you really support this lifetime? what really are your ethics, for your action is a direct reflection of it. #metoo? think about it
the next shirt will say bikram is the name of a rapist, not a method of yoga. .
#yoga #accountability #teach #ahimsa #nonharm #holdstrong

i'm excited to share publishers weekly's review of we shall see the sky sparkling, my debut historical novel... üå±‚ú®‚ú®üìñ‚Å£
‚Å£
"aikin‚Äôs satisfying debut follows the life of a young woman who defies her father and leaves home to become an actress. in 1897 manchester, england, 17-year old lily throop travels to london, where she finds work as an actress at the imperial theater. lily is eventually cast in a leading role, though she must also endure the erratic and abusive behavior of her fellow actor and mentor, herbert wade. though lily enjoys the freedom to make her own life and career decisions, her success is threatened when scandal surrounding her relationship with stagehand chut leads her to flee england and join a theater group in st. petersburg in pre-revolutionary russia. while in st. petersburg, lily falls under the spell of aristocrat and revolutionary sergei nikolayevich. their passionate relationship is complicated by the fact that he is married and by his belief that his revolutionary plans are more important than his relationship with lily. ultimately, lily must decide whether to stay with him and continue their relationship despite the danger he faces. aikin‚Äôs novel is expertly plotted and rife with historical details in both its english and russian settings, making for a rich story of the prejudices women faced at the turn of the 20th century and how the class disparity in russia ignited the flame of revolution."‚Å£
.‚Å£

text:
be the person you needed when you were younger. be the kind of person you would depend on and turn to for help. | jiu-jitsu has saved my life in so many ways, but most importantly, it has allowed me to live a life of passion and purpose. mentorship matters deeply to me, though i often underestimate my ability to influence others. i have went through so many experiences that left me feeling broken, have made countless mistakes, and have struggled with myself for so long that i believed that i was not worthy of being loved or looked at. as much as i wanted to run away from my pain, it wasn‚Äôt until i accepted my trauma that i could heal, mature, and move on. i didn‚Äôt know i wanted to be a mentor. i just knew that i didn‚Äôt want anyone else to feel the isolation and helplessness that i felt. i was 13 when i was first sexually assaulted and i didn‚Äôt break my silence until i was 26. at 32, i have a voice, i have a platform, and i have a mission. the most important title i will ever have will always be ‚Äúrole model‚Äù. | check out my full interview along side my bff @erinherle with @banuaprojects by checking out their youtube channel. link available in their bio.
.
.
.

text:
meet nelini stamp, our #wokewednesday feature for today.
.
this woman is a powerhouse of action and strength. as the national organizing director at the working families party, nelini collaborates with volunteer leaders across the country to build local progressive infrastructure. she joined the new york working families party staff in 2008, door knocking and field organizing for a variety of electoral campaigns across new york state. since then, she has been deeply involved in social movement work around economic and racial justice across the country.
.
nelini also co-created the freedom side and co-founded dream defenders in florida, which organizes and trains youth in non-violent civil disobedience, civic engagement, and direct action. lately, as a co-builder of wfp's resist here project, which launched #resisttrumptuesdays, she has been chasing senator schumer around to make sure he stands up to trump. you can often find her leading marches, attending rallies, and mic-checking at direct actions.
.
you can learn more about this amazing woman, follow, and support her at @nelstamp.

text:
i was 18 years old when i found out first hand how incredibly intrusive, invasive, violating, and humiliating vaginal exams like pelvic exams and pap smears are. i found this out after a doctor bullied and coerced me into having a pelvic exam i had already made clear i did not want. i felt like i'd been assaulted and vowed i'd never have one again. 
this kind of bullying, coercion, and lack of consent is extremely common in gynecological situations for many women. especially when young women go to thier doctors seeking birth control, they are often faced with a medically unnecessary and invasive exam. trans men are often faced with the same struggle when looking for hrt prescriptions.
it's my mission to make sure that nobody has to go through a nonconsensual vaginal exam ever again.
#womenempowerment #womenshealth #consent #feminism #feminist #transgender #transrights #birthcontrol #metoo #papsmear #gynecology #endsexualviolence #endsexualassault #antibullying #wedeservebetter #nomore
name: The Wrong Side of the Speculum

text:
spend the #summer researching with our #uofutransform faculty, earn a $4000 stipend, and gain 10-weeks intensive research experience with @uofu_our. .
.
application to apply this friday, jan. 25. letter of recommendation define is wed., jan. 30. link in bio for more info. here‚Äôs one project spotlight with dr. sarah projansky, associate professor in gender studies and fine arts.
.
.
the history, present, & future of title ix's role in addressing sexual misconduct on university campuses
.
.
this project examines the association between title ix and sexual misconduct in four contexts. (1) it looks at arguments made in court cases (1972-pesent) that use title ix to protect against sexual misconduct. (2) it analyzes office of civil rights (ocr) documents and investigations to identify how the ocr sets the parameters of title ix's role in protecting against sexual misconduct, parameters that expanded significantly 2011-2016 but have since diminished and are now in limbo. (3) it explores strategies various universities have used, are using, and are planning to use to address sexual misconduct during this time of rapid change, in part by interviewing title ix coordinators. and, (4) it looks at both mainstream and feminist media coverage of title ix and sexual misconduct, including, for example, news programs, humor on youtube, and social media activism. the overall goals of this project are (1) to develop a clear picture of the strengths and weaknesses of title ix's ability to protect against sexual misconduct, (2) to understand how decades of feminist activism have influenced judicial, federal, and educational policy and practices, as well as media representations and public opinion, and (3) to use history, analysis, and interviews to identify best practices going forward. this project is particularly important currently both because sexual misconduct has been highly visible since the #metoo movement began, as well as because title ix rules are currently in transition.

this picture captured the most authentic posture of my thought mind. i am always thinking, in my head, pondering the next move of life. why? because i know life is not checkers its chess! that being said combing through my thoughts being careful not to make the same mistakes over and over, praying because it is and always will be in god i trust! 
who am i... i am a warrior, a deliverer, a healer, a survivor, a beacon of light, a cycle breaker, and a bridge gapping trail blazer!
i am jabrita shelton the founder and ceo of real women moving forward, and i have a story to tell. 
more to come... this one you dont want to miss!

text: ‚Äúi walked into my homeroom class wearing a sweater over this top," says leah, 15, from san francisco. "i was scared to take the sweater off because i knew there was a likely chance someone would comment on my tank top. i had worn this outfit for a reason: it was 80 degrees, and i knew the classrooms would be sweltering. i was correct: the classroom was unbearably hot. therefore, i got over my fear and took off my sweater. almost immediately, my teacher asked me to come to her desk. i put my sweater back on as i walked over to her. she told me that she was about to tell me to cover up because what i was wearing was ‚Äòa little showy.‚Äô i nodded and returned to my desk. every day i walk past boys in the halls wearing their pants so low that you can see their boxers. they don‚Äôt get called out.‚Äù @leahm1tch3ll ***have you been #dresscoded or experienced #slutshaming because of your clothing? message or email me (leoratan@yahoo.com) if you want to participate in this project. *** for more information, click on link in bio. #slutbashing #everydaysexism #schooldresscode #dresscode #beingdresscoded  #stoprape #rapeculture #metoo #notaskingforit #feminism #sexism #leoratanenbaum

text:
thank you @laura_bates__ for writing about ndas in the @guardian today. 
this is the story i sent to laura from the pts archives:

i was working for a ftse100 company at a senior level. i had been a dedicated, high achieving employee for 6 years with an exemplary record of achievement, so when i discovered i was pregnant i wasn‚Äôt worried about my career. it is clear to me now how unbelievably naive i was. from the moment i announced my pregnancy things turned sour. my boss could barely make eye contact with me, i became a burden to him and the business. they sidelined me from meetings and started to give some of my work to a more junior, male member of my team without any discussion. they chipped away at my confidence, making backhanded comments about my appearance and my work ethic, which hadn‚Äôt changed. my personal development review was substandard when it had previously been excellent. there was no real explanation as why. i knew the stress of it all was getting to me and i was concerned about my health & the health of the baby so i kept my head down & waited until maternity leave, hoping that when i returned things would be back to normal. six weeks after my baby was born i received an email. the email wasn‚Äôt meant for me, it had been sent to me by accident. it was a discussion between my boss & the hr department. my boss wanted to make me redundant & said i wouldn‚Äôt make a fuss as i was on maternity leave & probably wanted to leave anyway. he had realised his mistake & invited me in for a meeting. i dragged myself there with my baby daughter, i was still in pain from the birth, having had 3 hours sleep. i was so confused & exhausted i barely remember how i got there or what was said. 
they offered me money and a good reference as long as i signed an nda. they said that this was the best offer i would get, more than what redundancy would pay so i should take it and enjoy my time on maternity leave. they would make sure my reference was good. 18 months later i am still unemployed & i have suffered post natal depression which i know was triggered by this incident. i feel guilty that i allowed them to get away with it. what message am i sending to my daughter?
name: Joeli Brearley

i was working for a ftse100 company at a senior level. i had been a dedicated, high achieving employee for 6 years with an exemplary record of achievement, so when i discovered i was pregt i wasn‚Äôt worried about my career. it is clear to me now how unbelievably naive i was. from the moment i announced my pregcy things turned sour. my boss could barely make eye contact with me, i became a burden to him and the business. they sidelined me from meetings and staed to give some of my work to a more junior, male member of my team without any discussion. they chipped away at my confidence, making backhanded comments about my appearance and my work ethic, which hadn‚Äôt changed. my personal development review was substandard when it had previously been excellent. there was no real explanation as why. i knew the stress of it all was getting to me and i was concerned about my health & the health of the baby so i kept my head down & waited until maternity leave, hoping that when i returned things would be back to normal. six weeks after my baby was born i received an email. the email wasn‚Äôt meant for me, it had been sent to me by accident. it was a discussion between my boss & the hr depament. my boss wanted to make me redundant & said i wouldn‚Äôt make a fuss as i was on maternity leave & probably wanted to leave anyway. he had realised his mistake & invited me in for a meeting. i dragged myself there with my baby daughter, i was still in pain from the bih, having had 3 hours sleep. i was so confused & exhausted i barely remember how i got there or what was said. 
they offered me money and a good reference as long as i signed an nda. they said that this was the best offer i would get, more than what redundancy would pay so i should take it and enjoy my time on maternity leave. they would make sure my reference was good. 18 months later i am still unemployed & i have suffered post natal depression which i know was triggered by this incident. i feel guilty that i allowed them to get away with it. what message am i sending to my daughter?

text:
my theme this week is change. last week i talked in my posts on the theme of emotion and how it's a catalyst to change. 
this week i make two important points about change. first, that the approach you design to navigate change must fit the change desired and the makeup of the stakeholders you serve. in the podcast episode (link in bio) i share a story about using one of the more subtle approaches. but sometimes an aspirational approach, like the #metoo movement or the #womensmarch, which are often a blunter instrument is more effective. but there are many more available to you.

secondly, in my various post this week we explore the impact of the change-back reaction. this phenomenon, which is as old as human existence is one for which you want to have a strategy regardless of the approach you're adopting.

#change #selfawareness #selfregulation #selfworth #curiosity #belonging #resilience #presence #connecting #makeithappen #unpack4impact #meaning

text:
call for participants 
for the panty project
.
the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work addresses the inherent misogyny within our language, and the consequential "essestializing" of womxn, which reduces womxn, and those who identify as womxn, to "less than." this work is about healing and transcendence. 
womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

text:
domestic violence laws in california do not protect stepparents! help make strangulation a felony!

a planned and manipulated scheme to take my stepdaughter away from her mom. wow. talk about aggressive. it‚Äôs because every time we would talk to her about my stepdaughter‚Äôs / her god daughter‚Äôs challenges with her mom, stepdad and subsequently her learning at school she would say she didn‚Äôt want to be involved for years so we kept it to ourselves. she asked us to please not ask her to come to court, that she needs to focus on her family and getting that deeply involved isn‚Äôt the right decision or supportive of her family. 
then she turns around and comes to every family court session, writes letters to court, takes the stand against us all the while saying she is doing it to be a neutral party and is dismissed as a non-party and hearsay. she was went as far as to email my husband‚Äôs son court papers to intentionally damage that bond. 
how is this a neutral party for her 12 year old god child? i promise you she never had a conversation with her goddaughter to learn it was she who wanted this change before all this happened. she felt more supported and did so well in school while at our house. 
the courts findings after 11 months of nonsense that cost our family in the excess of $35k in just court fees was that we were credible and aurelia was not. our declaration and testimonies aligned with the 911 call and the police that came and also testified. therefore we were granted a domestic violence restraining order and she was denied her bogus efforts. 
we didn‚Äôt need to spend $35k in court and the only reason why it cost that much was because aurelia with debbie (and others who also came) had to try that hard to convince the court that she was the victim and that plan failed in both courts.

text:
(try to leave be the two typos later in the video, keep in mind the actual message, posting this again to reach more people)  i need to apologize ahead of time if this video offends anyone, but the truth of the matter is that it's absolutely vital for people to be informed of how close to home some atrocities truly are. protect your family, your friends and your community a all costs. i decided with life constantly throwing me opportunities to do good or turn a blind eye that i was going to put myself in the fire intentionally. within 24 hrs of signing up to a local date site pretending to be a 14 year old boy named brayden i was contacted by a supposed 27-29 year old man named vicky... i informed the authorities i was to meet him in half an hr and even with me being informed that the dispatch wasn't sure if i could be charged i set forth to the destination of the rendezvous.... my only intent was to hopefully have buddy charged for luring  minor and to have consequences for his inappropriate intentions, though given  the lack of incriminating text log conversation no charges were able to be applied.. regardless , if nothing else he is on the records for a complaint regarding such a topic.  im aware of defamation of character clause, but if he can't be charged for his actions, i'll be dammed to believe if i blur out his face i can be prosecuted against. lashed for speaking out and creating awareness to poorly suited characters who cannot be trusted, nor deserve the right to continually offend due to loop holes in the system.. this is an awareness post, not  a hate post. 
thank you , for your time

https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=t9efk0tetbm  be well  believe in your moments  believe in today  we are all worthy

‚Ä¢
as an experienced nurse i have witnessed each and every one of these things. i have intervened and i have not. i have reported these behaviors and i have not. i have called attention to these behaviors in my peers and i have not.
‚Ä¢
how can we discuss #metoo without discussing obstetrical violence? what is obstetrical violence? how overt or subtle is it? how widespread?
‚Ä¢
i speak bout birthing justice, implicit bias, #blackbirthmatters, and about obstetrical violence - because i‚Äôve witnessed it. we need a change before we can hope to see an improvement. ever since i began nursing, i‚Äôve watched care providers (nurses, midwives and doctors) pass the buck. i have, too. we minimize physical and emotional trauma and we aren‚Äôt accountable for our role. we can provide excellent, safe care while ensuring birthing people‚Äôs rights and humanity. in fact, we cannot keep them safe, unless we do. ‚Ä¢

text: cardi b defended her ‚Äútwerk‚Äù video to a daily caller employee on twitter, clapping back to say that the visuals say ‚Äúto women that i can wear and not wear what ever i want‚Äù and ‚Äúno still means no.‚Äù daily caller video columnist stephanie hamill tweeted about the music video for the song ‚Äútwerk‚Äù by city girls featuring cardi b, which dropped last week. hamill‚Äôs initial tweet included a clip of the video where many scantily clad women are twerking. ‚Äúin the era of #metoo how exactly does this empower women?‚Äù asked hamill, before imploring leftists and cardi b to chime in. considering cardi‚Äôs recent response to conservative commentator tomi lahren wherein she told lahren that she would ‚Äúdog walk‚Äù her if she didn‚Äôt leave cardi alone, it‚Äôs not surprising that the rapper answered hamill‚Äôs call. the 26-year-old told hamill that the video was about women having agency over their bodies and asked if hamill personally thinks that twerking half-naked means she deserves to get ‚Äúraped and molested.‚Äù hamill responded by saying that she agrees that ‚Äúno means no, no matter what‚Äù but that she believes the video sexually objectifies women, and that ‚Äúhurts all women & the cause.‚Äù ‚Äúwe‚Äôre not sex objects!‚Äù said hamill, who also added that perhaps she‚Äôs just a hater because she can‚Äôt twerk. she also asked for cardi to come on her show and debate.

text: you‚Äôre never alone. you‚Äôre always enough. you deserve to live. you deserve better. life gets better. üíó one year ago i was in the verge of a 6 month+ long mental breakdown, an absolute collapse in my mental and physical health. a period that nearly took my life twice, and was without a doubt the worst period of my life thus far. today, i started classes for my last spring semester, this month i started an independent study that i‚Äôm blessed and proud to be a part of, i took a trip to plan out my future, and i started therapy to get the help i‚Äôve needed for way too long and i got a mark on my body that i look at everyday to remind me that i am in control. i already can‚Äôt wait to wake up tomorrow and the next day and so on to do what i have to do because i‚Äôm so f*cking thankful to be alive and to have the opportunities that i have. 2018 sucked, but i made it, and i won‚Äôt hide how proud i am of that. blog post on this coming this week. sorry for the long winded post, but i saw this quote on @girlbossempires and needed to share it. i don‚Äôt even care if you don‚Äôt know me personally, message me if you need someone. message a friend. message a family member, so see a professor, coworker, boss, doctor, anyone. tell someone if you‚Äôre not okay. make a call 1-800-273-8255 if you can‚Äôt do it alone or if you can‚Äôt or don‚Äôt want to talk to anyone you know. a call can save your life, and you deserve to live happily. #suicideprevention #suicideawareness #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealth #selfconfidence #selflove #reachout #speakup #sexualassaultawareness #domesticviolenceawareness #depressionawareness #loveyourself #metoo

text: so the oscar nominations came out yesterday...and ugh. i almost wish they'd gone through with the "most popular film" category because this years best picture race is total bs. first of all, the academy has 10 total slots for best picture, and this year they picked 8. why? i have no idea. but i hate it. bohemian crapsody got nominated in this category over if beale street could talk, first reformed, eighth grade, hereditary, etc. they nominated black panther which is cool, but not as deserving as other films. so many snubs this year...i'm back to being on the fence about the oscar's again. last year they did such a good job recognizing the true artistic films, and this year we go right back to wtf? i think the academy was so worried about backlash that they voted while trying to appease the masses. big mistake. so many of the choices are just baffling. bohemian rhapsody should not have been nominated in 3 of its 5 categories. the sound mixing and sound editing are fair. but best editing? laughable. best actor for rami malek? over ethan hawke (first reformed) and john david washington (blackkklansman)? not to mention the film was made by a serial pedophile...what the hell were you thinking academy? a year after the #metoo campaign? this just shows how short of a memory span hollywood has. toni collette also was snubbed for hereditary which in my opinion is still the best female lead performance of last year. in the directing category i was angry to see them snub barry jenkins for beale street but i was happy to see spike lee finally get the nod for blackkklansman. but the most pleasant surprise was the favourite and roma getting 10 nominations a piece. huge deal for netflix. also the buster scruggs nods were awesome. overall i'm very disappointed with most of the choices this year. but that's the film business i guess. #oscars #trash #nominations #hotgarbage #disappointed #academyawards
name: christianswim (LoneAstronaut)

text:
what is male privilege? what is toxic male masculinity? how does it feel to have a commercial suggest how you as a man can improve? it's certainly like women don't have any commercials or adverts like that, right? .
i originally believed i would share this story on my personal ig yet soon realized i wouldn't be being my true self, i wouldn't be standing up for women, i wouldn't be rising in solidarity. take a stand‚úä
.

this weekend i attended a very important music show & it was absolutely incredible. the show brought together so many people in love+peace+and unity, it truly was beautiful. i personally ran into so many people i haven't seen in years!!! so what's the problem you ask? ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.

the problem is i was violated. all night long i was violated by multiple men. in one night men grabbed, slapped, or pinched my ass. 1 man engaged in too many uncomfortable embraces that eventually lead to me trying to squirm out of his hold. i during this time messaged the closest person in my life (a male) who advised me if i didn't "like" it i could leave. um... excuse me? so what you're saying is 'cause i'm a female and there is a handful of very i'll behaved men at this show, i should leave!? & if i don't, i'm asking for it??! ü§¨
.
.

i'm by no means the feminist of the year. i'd personally love to be a stay at home ma, making jewelry all day+cooking dinner & there isn't anything wrong with that. unfortunately for me, i'm a single mom. everything i have i've worked my booty off for and i'm tired of being victimized by humans that haven't an oz of common decency and respect and you all should be too! üê∑
.
.

was i asking for it!? well, if we are still asking these type of questions then we are missing the point entirely but my high waisted velvet bell bottoms are going to suggest i wasn't dressed provocatively...was i asking for it in college when i would hear "but she is so friendly and bubbly so i thought..." (no, spoiler alert, i act the same way to males, females, babies, cats, dogs, my mother, my father) and since we still ask that question...here i am, at an amazing boudoir shoot and guess what, i'm still not asking for it. #metoo #mybodymyvoice

text:
yesssss. this is so rarely discussed as well. the negative response to the #gillette ad puts this in stark relief. the pushback on #metoo. the emotional labor it takes to bring these topics up with many men in a gentle way to avoid them lashing out. and so on and so on.... this is a unique moment, and rife with difficulties that i have compassion for. we are telling men that the rules to the game they‚Äôve grown up with are changing mid-play. it‚Äôs confusing. we are all a little confused. more reason to keep talking. more reason to focus on boys and how they are raised. we all benefit when the binaries around gender are loosened and are fluid. 
this is from yesterday‚Äôs @nytimes piece ‚Äú what is toxic masculity‚Äù by @maya__salam : 
so what does ‚Äútoxic masculinity,‚Äù or ‚Äútraditional masculinity ideology,‚Äù mean? researchers have defined it, in part, as a set of behaviors and beliefs that include the following: ‚Ä¢ suppressing emotions or masking distress
‚Ä¢ maintaining an appearance of hardness
‚Ä¢ violence as an indicator of power (think: ‚Äútough-guy‚Äù behavior). in other words: toxic masculinity is what can come of teaching boys that they can‚Äôt express emotion openly; that they have to be ‚Äútough all the time‚Äù; that anything other than that makes them ‚Äúfeminine‚Äù or weak. (no, it doesn‚Äôt mean that all men are inherently toxic.) - maya salam 
#stayhuman #keepshowingup

"cardi b defended her ‚Äútwerk‚Äù video to a daily caller employee on twitter, clapping back to say that the visuals say ‚Äúto women that i can wear and not wear what ever i want‚Äù and ‚Äúno still means no.‚Äù daily caller video columnist stephanie hamill tweeted about the music video for the song ‚Äútwerk‚Äù by city girls featuring cardi b, which dropped last week. hamill‚Äôs initial tweet included a clip of the video where many scantily clad women are twerking. ‚Äúin the era of #metoo how exactly does this empower women?‚Äù asked hamill, before imploring leftists and cardi b to chime in. considering cardi‚Äôs recent response to conservative commentator tomi lahren wherein she told lahren that she would ‚Äúdog walk‚Äù her if she didn‚Äôt leave cardi alone, it‚Äôs not surprising that the rapper answered hamill‚Äôs call. the 26-year-old told hamill that the video was about women having agency over their bodies and asked if hamill personally thinks that twerking half-naked means she deserves to get ‚Äúraped and molested.‚Äù hamill responded by saying that she agrees that ‚Äúno means no, no matter what‚Äù but that she believes the video sexually objectifies women, and that ‚Äúhurts all women & the cause.‚Äù ‚Äúwe‚Äôre not sex objects!‚Äù said hamill, who also added that perhaps she‚Äôs just a hater because she can‚Äôt twerk. she also asked for cardi to come on her show and debate."

text:
about the book 
in the woman in the mirror, author evelyn mejil provides a vivid portrait of her courageous mind meeting her painful memories, her valiant heart overcoming her shameful unworthiness, and her bold spirit overpowering her relentless fear.
in this account, mejil shares an uncensored description of how she overcomes her past when she discovers an inconspicuous truth while traveling the world in search for answers to silence her nightmares and heal her pain. hidden in the eyes of the woman reflected in the mirror, she sees the answers stood where she buried her painful past, and to find them there is only one journey left to take, a journey within.
the woman in the mirror tells how once she goes beyond the memories and faces her demons, she finally discovers her true being and vividly recounts how her false self, the identity birthed in the lies of her past, collapses. shattering the iron grip of her past, she heals and brings forth a new story. mejil presents the unadulterated expression of her most powerful self, the authentic self.
order your copy today by visiting: evelynmejil.com link in bio üîù

text:
next painting in the series i've been working on this morning. 
i said stop... he didn't....
are you sure it was rape?
liar
this painting is for all of us women out there who've been sexually abused, raped, and who've dealt with people not believing them.  the questions asked, such as "are you sure?", are one way we perpetuate rape culture in today's world.  according to the national sexual violence resource center one in five women will be raped at some point in their lives, 51.1% of those by a partner, and 63% of all rape incidents go unreported. (https://www.nsvrc.org/statistics)
rape victims have a hard time reporting, and there are many reasons why.  one of those reasons is people questioning the legitimacy of their claim.  stop the cycle, believe victims, support victims and start the conversation of how we can change the way we handle rape cases.

text:
- sure, you can run to the other side where the grass is green. but eventually, if you don't work on it, if you don't make a change, if you don't water that grass and feed it, even the other side with beautiful green grass will lose its colour.  no matter where you are or where you go, no matter how green the grass is on the other side, and no matter how beautiful the other side is, if you're are not happy with your grass & you keep doing the same thing, you will keep getting the same end result time and time again. the grass is not greener on the other side, the grass is greener where you water it, it's greener where you make an effort to better yourself, it‚Äôs greener where you love yourself first. you could be on dry land and still grow green grass. it's not about where you are or where you go, it‚Äôs not about another side being where you most desire to be. it is about how you get rid of those old weeds, it's about letting those weeds go because you now know that they are only preventing the grass from growing, it's about realising that these weeds serve you no purpose, and only you have the power to get rid of those weeds. but most of all, it is about how you stop feeding the weeds that serve you no purpose and how you begin to feed the present healthy roots that give the grass growth, and that my friends, is what makes a true difference. 
prioritise yourself - work your little ass off - focus on your side of the grass and be busy. so busy that you‚Äôre too busy watering your own grass to notice anyone else‚Äôs side üå± #thegrassisgreen #bentbutnotbreaking #love #motivationalspeaker #inspirationalquotes #metoo #lifequotes #parenting #mentalillness  #advocate #awareness

text:
by formally entering the presidential race, kamala harris immediately becomes one of the front-runners for the democratic nomination. as nate silver recently explained, harris has the potential to fare well among several of the five big democratic constituencies: party loyalists; hard-core progressives; young voters; african-americans; and hispanic and asian-american voters.‚Å£
‚Å£
so take her candidacy seriously. but once you‚Äôve done so, i would encourage you to mostly ignore whether she is likely to win and focus your attention instead on whether she deserves to win. make your own decisions about the candidates, rather than trying to guess what other voters will do.‚Å£
‚Å£
harris has signaled that she is likely to run a more thematically broad-based, less focused campaign than some others. elizabeth warren and bernie sanders (if he runs) will focus on inequality and economic justice, for example. joe biden would probably emphasize his experience and electability. kirsten gillibrand has centered her pitch partly on #metoo. the harris campaign, for now, is looking less specific ‚Äî which has both downsides and benefits.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚Äúnobody is living their life through the lens of one issue,‚Äù she said yesterday. ‚Äúand i think what people want is leadership that sees them through the complexity of their lives and pays equal attention to their needs. let‚Äôs not put people in a box.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
‚Äî david leonhardt, @nytimes ‚Å£
‚Å£
[credit: alex brandon/ap photo]

text:
for the alternate audio tour we created for our guerrilla performance at the art institute of chicago, which calls for the museum to present the truth behind the floating worlds exhibition, i was lucky enough to interview dr. amy stanley, a professor from northwestern university focused on japanese history. she provided the facts about the horrific living conditions the women and girls in the paintings endured. 
power dynamics in museums, racism, sexism, and homophobia are a few of the reasons museums withhold information from exhibitions, or choose to present primarily the work of white male artists. 
here is a short clip taken by one of the performers playing the alternate audio tour out loud at the exhibition while viewing the work. @amystanley5520

text:
r. kelly is sick and should be in a prison but what about this guy?ü§∑üèæ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è lawsuit charges donald trump with raping a 13-year-old girl

a civil suit against donald trump alleging he raped a 13-year-old girl was dismissed in california in may 2016, refiled in new york in june 2016, and dropped again in november 2016.

a federal lawsuit filed in new york accuses republican presidential candidate donald trump of repeatedly raping a 13-year-old girl more than 20 years ago, at several upper east side parties hosted by convicted sex offender and notorious billionaire investor jeffrey epstein.
the suit, first reported by the real deal, accuses trump and epstein of luring the anonymous plaintiff and other young women to four parties at epstein‚Äôs so-called wexner mansion at 9 east 71st street. epstein allegedly lured the plaintiff, identified in the suit only as jane doe, with promises of a modeling career and cash.
another anonymous woman, identified in additional testimony as tiffany doe, corroborates jane‚Äôs allegations, testifying that she met epstein at port authority, where he hired her to recruit other young girls for his parties. trump had known epstein for seven years in 1994 when he attended the parties at wexner, according to the suit. he also allegedly knew that the plaintiff was 13 years old.

because falling into something because of chemistry or loneliness or some shared interests just isn‚Äôt enough. 
we study and research for our jobs and think. relationship should be an innate ability we are born with. 
it‚Äôs not. üòâ
so, how does he show up? 
this one took me a while but i‚Äôm kind of stubborn üòä

text:
it's so amazing to look and feel great at 38. women are told they are unattractive and too old as they get closer to 40 but i don't think it's true at all. 
i have never felt younger or more beautiful than right now. sobriety is literally the most amazing wellness plan in the world that no one is utilizing. 
i used to think that being the size i used to be in college was impossible but now those don't fit me, they are too big. don't let anyone tell you what is possible in your own body. 
everyone except for a few close friends and my amazing trainer @delbarka told me transformation was impossible and financial freedom was a pipe dream but they were only talking about themselves. you can redefine what is possible for yourself any day of the year!

#drydiet #sober #nohangover #noalcohol #metoo #transformation #dopamine #addictionrecovery #onedayatatime #recoveroutloud #happybirthday

text:
survivor.

it‚Äôs a label i wear without shame. i lived, i made it through, i survived what should have destroyed me. i made mistakes. there is no way to go back and make all of my shattered pieces pretty. i‚Äôve been putting myself back together and using my faith in god, and the strength he has given me as the  glue in my reconstruction. intense pain fueled my self-destruction and my entire life was  controlled by that pain‚Äîpain and trauma that i was powerless to for many years of my childhood. 
today, though, i have a voice. many, many people are much more comfortable with that voice being silenced, but i refuse to live in the darkness of that shame ever again. it is only in the light that we heal. we turn the tables on our monsters when we live in the light of the truth‚Äîtruth always wins in the end. 
don‚Äôt ever live in sadness or shame over something that was done to you. like me, i‚Äôm sure you have the scars, both physical and emotional, that you will carry with you forever. that‚Äôs ok, but don‚Äôt you ever, not for one second longer, think that you are less-than, or not worthy of love. 
so for all of my soul sisters and brothers out there who have walked this path of trauma and healing alongside me, i love you. i pray for you many times each day. your pain matters. you matter.  you deserved better and you are not alone. 
i stand by you. üí™‚ù§Ô∏è #youhavesuchaprettyface #happinessisaninsidejob #ptsd #ptsdawareness #ptsdrecovery #healingjourney #abusesurvivor #selfworth #trustgod #sprinkleofjesus #gettingthroughit #gettingbetter #strongertogether #braveheart #courageous #womanempowerment #womanwarrior #iwillsurvive #itgetsbetter #metoo #silencetheshame #standbyme #strengthinnumbers #myvoice #victims #standstrong #positivemindset #iamworthy

text:
there is almost no better feeling that i get than to nurture my relationship with corn and feed other mothers. 
the love of a mother is like nothing else.  the sacrificing starts in the womb and the care a mother has to take to grow a child. it never ends. 
when i get sick, i give all that i have left in my weak body to feed, nourish, and heal my child all hours of the day and night. so much so, that my system fails to protect itself and i fall apart. 
but maiz taught me the power of a mother before having my son, and the healing power of not only a mother who has given birth but the power of being a daughter of the great mother. 
i still remember the exact night, taking a walk trying to recover from my rape and find my power again. i looked over and the giant corn stalks waved in the wind and i saw her brute strength and magnificence while at the same time swaying with grace and whispers so sweet. she whispered, ‚Äúi am greater than him.‚Äù i saw a power that went beyond me, and what i experienced as mother corn taught me what power felt like again. i was almost scared it was so shocking. 
i then went to the land and fasted to seek more refuge and healing, to learn more about using the power of mother earth to heal myself. on day four i dropped to my knees into the red dirt with tears pouring down and asked ‚Äúwhat can i do of the pain in the world of women who suffer from physical abuse and the robbery of their body?‚Äú i heard the same sweet whisper, ‚Äúbuild refuge and feed them.‚Äù ‚Äúmama‚Äù is a first utterance in almost every language in the world in babies, which linguists believe is a sound that derives from a baby breastfeeding (it is a slight nasal murmur - you can hear it) and is therefore first actually correlated with the baby‚Äôs understanding of food. mama, mother, ama (navajo), eomma (korean), mama (swahili)‚Ä¶ etc. etc. almost every language the same word. 
so mama‚Äôs, i honor you. women seeking to gain their power back again after abuse, it‚Äôs still a struggle for me, but i have more power now than ever. gratitude for the last of this huge 2016 crop that has fed so many.

text:
this was september 2012.  upon launching my beauty business, i realized very quickly that every face has a story.  i realized the work and business that i was embarking upon was more than applying makeup, i was being groomed to the ‚Äúministry of beauty‚Äù.
.
as my client sat in my chair and i began to remove her old makeup - to clean her face and prepare for glam, i noticed a scar.  as i continued to wipe, she told me that she doesn‚Äôt always wear full face makeup, but one thing she won‚Äôt leave home without is concealer over her scar.
.
somberly, she went on to tell me how her ex-husband used to ‚Äúbeat her face‚Äù and the scar is a constant reminder of her pain and trauma, therefore it‚Äôs always covered with makeup üò¢. i hugged her, told her that i appreciated her sharing her story and told her she was beautiful and brave. .
from that day, i never associated my work or words with the phrase ‚Äúbeat face‚Äù. now i know it‚Äôs a part of the makeup industry lexicon - makeup artists day it all the time & clients excitedly love to say ‚Äúi want so and so to beat my face‚Äù. i know it‚Äôs just something we say and it has a different meaning & tone historically but the idea of the phrase for me, took on another meaning that day, so i don‚Äôt ever say it or want it associated with my work.  many people in this industry know that is my stance - always has been, always will be.
.
so yes, every face has story and i am grateful that my gift of makeup artistry has a bigger purpose and i have the power to transform, with the stroke of a brush, someone‚Äôs pain into beauty. ‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
note to self: be healthy. 
you may notice i didn‚Äôt say eat healthy. in 2002 i weighed 391 pounds.  i lost 243 pounds and i‚Äôve maintained that loss for 17 years now. in my continuing journey of healing and becoming my very best me, i‚Äôve realized that what i am eating is only one very small component in making myself whole. 
in hindsight,  losing the weight has probably been the easiest part of my getting healthy. yes i had surgery and no, that is not easy. the critical piece, that some people find hard to admit,  is that i had to heal what caused me to use food as comfort in the first place. until i did that, i just kept branching out into other equally unhealthy behaviors and emotions. i might have been thin, but i certainly wasn‚Äôt happy. i was moody and bitchy all the time. i was in a constant stream of high stress and anger. i felt powerless, but i tried to usurp that feeling by attempting to control everything and everyone around me. it didn‚Äôt work. i was so unhappy and i made most people around me unhappy. that‚Äôs why none of my relationships ever worked out. no one wanted to listen or deal with my drama all day long.  no one wants to take on all that stress. people are attracted to light, peace, and joy‚Äînot negativity. 
once i dug in deep and finally began to work through the pain and trauma from my childhood, that is when the light at the end of the tunnel appeared. yes, there was hope.  healing has many obstacles and is the hardest thing i‚Äôve ever done, but it‚Äôs also the healthiest thing i‚Äôve ever done. don‚Äôt become thin and still be unhealthy. do all the work.

finally, a commercial that gets it! (well, i half agree with it - it applies to everyone not just guys!) it's not cool to disrupt someone with the intention of a compliment while they're about doing their business. i hate comps for that very reason - both getting, and giving.

this isn't about never talking to a woman or anyone - i talk to ppl all the time! i say hi to people all the time! if they can't hang, oh well! but i don't talk or approach in that 'flirty' objectifying harassey way!
.
(at the very least, i know sbu will agree with me here b/c the institution had always been against me getting a g/f, period, in the past - the environment is friendly but a learning environment only, not a meeting ppl in that way one!)
.

text:
mgtow 101:  generational wealth gap increases with each black professional degree

i might take heat from 95% of y'all niggas on this one but let me take a second to free your mind.
üëÇ
üëÇ
 most of these dudes are gonna be indoctrinated into the system and be zombies caught in the matrix. when you create your own business and manage to break away from the system of working under people then that's a positive black image. all these guys have to be integrated to actually find success.
üëÇ
üëÇ
those days are done with, we in the last days, and we still viewing debt slaves as accomplishments and pinnacles of success. they still gonna be working in the system and their mind is going to be fully assimilated into the system as well. as long as you are in the system they can take it away from you. they can discredit your degree in one second, look at umar johnson current problems.
üëÇ
üëÇ
i will say at least the engineer as skills that can build away from the system and the doctor is a trade that can save lives outside of the system. those are valuable skills, a lawyer is gonna have a difficult time getting a job, have bunch of debt and has no trade skills that can be applied outside of the profession. as a medic, i can still save a family member life when the system falls. that's an actual skill. construction workers can build a 500k house for 80k. build his own home. that's a skill.
üëÇ
üëÇ
businesses build generational wealth and photos like this are the same reason we don't have generational wealth. you can't pass down a 401k, pension or degree to your offspring, you better off owning a lawn mowing company that pay you 70k a year that can be passed to your kid. going to college is good if you gonna create your own, if you just wanna work in profession forever you thinking like a nigga. no matter your profession or degree you have to create a business for yourself.
üëÇ

mr tran van thi, is the founder of justice for lai dai han. as a lai dai han himself, he is a human rights activist for the victims of sexual violence in vietnam. 
one week ago, at the ldh event in the uk house of commons, he spoke on his experience;
"in 1989, they sent some officers on a fact finding mission in vietnam. those officers went into every single family with lai dai han children; they were asking for pictures, for notes, for anything that can be considered evidence. they took evidence away, and never gave recognition to the matter."
.

text: nations are often quoted as saying they don't negotiate with terrorists. well, we would like to submit that you can't negotiate with predators either, but yet so many people try and fail time and time again. how you ask? every time you hear about or witness some type of predatory behavior or blatant act of sexual abuse and turn a blind eye because the victim isn't your child, and you think your relationship with the predator will preclude them from harming your child, you are effectively trying to negotiate. every time you see or hear about predatory behavior or blatant sexual abuse in your own family or circle of friends and you choose to overlook the predator's actions because you think they aren't going to do it again, you are in essence trying to negotiate. however, your attempts to negotiate will always fail because predators have no boundaries. they don't care about familial relationships so your child won't be protected in exchange for your silence. when you see, hear, or know about predatory behavior or blatant sexual abuse, you have to speak up! otherwise, every child in the predator's path is in danger of being victimized. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #mlk

text:
üé¨ tonight! üé¨ **to rsvp click link in bio!**
we welcome you to this year‚Äôs pathways to vday auditions! pathways to vday is a multicultural and multilingual performance of eve ensler's "the vagina monologues". we are looking for brave female-identified/gender neutral individuals to join our pathways performance.

we are pleased to share that the vday.org leadership has given pathways for change, inc. special permission to perform this year in april for sexual assault awareness month! the 2018 performance was plagued by snow and ice, performing later in the year will hopefully get us through our messy snow season to ensure performers and audience safety. we are tremendously grateful to the vday.org team for their spirit and thoughtfulness. ‚Äúthe vagina monologues is made up of various personal monologues read by a diverse group of women. originally, eve ensler performed every monologue herself, with subsequent performances featuring three actresses, and more recent versions featuring a different actress for every role. each of the monologues deals with an aspect of the feminine experience, touching on matters such as sex, sex work, body image, love, rape, menstruation, female genital mutilation, masturbation, birth, orgasm, the various common names for the vagina or simply as a physical aspect of the body. a recurring theme throughout the piece is the vagina as a tool of female empowerment, and the ultimate embodiment of individuality." (thank you wikipedia)

to let us know if you are interested , visit: http://pathwaystovdayauditions.eventbrite.com/?s=90591445 
for questions/info: 
hleboeuf@pathwaysforchange.help or 508-852-7600

we welcome you to this year‚Äôs pathways to vday auditions! pathways to vday is a multicultural and multilingual performance of eve ensler's "the vagina monologues". we are looking for brave female-identified/gender neutral individuals to join our pathways performance.

we are pleased to share that the vday.org leadership has given pathways for change, inc. special permission to perform this year in april for sexual assault awareness month! the 2018 performance was plagued by snow and ice, performing later in the year will hopefully get us through our messy snow season to ensure performers and audience safety. we are tremendously grateful to the vday.org team for their spirit and thoughtfulness. ‚Äúthe vagina monologues is made up of various personal monologues read by a diverse group of women. originally, eve ensler performed every monologue herself, with subsequent performances featuring three actresses, and more recent versions featuring a different actress for every role. each of the monologues deals with an aspect of the feminine experience, touching on matters such as sex, sex work, body image, love, rape, menstruation, female genital mutilation, masturbation, birth, orgasm, the various common names for the vagina or simply as a physical aspect of the body. a recurring theme throughout the piece is the vagina as a tool of female empowerment, and the ultimate embodiment of individuality." (thank you wikipedia)

to let us know if you are interested , visit: http://pathwaystovdayauditions.eventbrite.com/?s=90591445
